It seems you are talking about a REST controller that returns JSON. With the default configuration, Spring Boot uses [Jackson][1] to transform objects to JSON. The most simple fix would be to tell Jackson to [ignore][2] the `password` field in your `User` class:

```
public class User {
    ...
    @JsonIgnore
    private String password;
    ...
}
```


See [this article][3] for more information.


  [1]: https://github.com/FasterXML/jackson-databind
  [2]: https://fasterxml.github.io/jackson-annotations/javadoc/2.5/com/fasterxml/jackson/annotation/JsonIgnore.html
  [3]: https://www.baeldung.com/jackson-ignore-properties-on-serialization#for_field

